data.title: How Martina Navratilova and Margaret Court went to war
data.meta_description: American tennis legend Martina Navratilova and Australian star Margaret Court are in a war of words after the latter player made a string of 'racist and homophobic' comments.
data.text:
Two tennis greats: One is openly gay and champions LGBT rights, the other has become an ordained (and outspoken) Christian minister since retiring.

Now they are engaged in a week-long battle after retired Australian tennis star Margaret Court made a string of 'racist and homophobic' insults about a lesbian player who had a child with her partner.

American tennis legend Martina Navratilova then kicked off a war of words with the Australian when she lashed out at the 74-year-old church pastor's 'sick and dangerous' comments on gays in tennis.

Court's statements have been widely criticised in the tennis world and prompted calls to rename Melbourne's Margaret Court Arena, or even boycott the venue at next year's open Grand Slam.

The controversy started when Court, who became a Christian pastor after retiring from tennis, drew fire for saying she will avoid Australian airline Qantas over its gay chief executive Alan Joyce's pro-gay marriage stance.

Then a newspaper clipping emerged on Friday of a letter to the editor Court wrote about Casey Dellacqua and her partner, who recently had a child together.

In the letter, Court used scare quotes to say she has nothing wrong with Dellacqua 'or her 'partner',' but that their baby with two mothers shouldn't have been 'deprived of her father'.

Dellacqua returned serve on Friday.

'Margaret. Enough is enough,' the mother wrote alongside the a photo of the newspaper clipping.

In the letter, 74-year-old Court, who once praised apartheid, said diverse families were 'engineering social norms'.

'Personally, I have nothing against Casey Dellacqua or her 'partner'.'

But Court, a Christian pastor, suggested children of diverse families aren't 'given the best possible start in life'.

'It is with sadness that I see that this baby has seemingly been deprived of a father,' Court, a Christian pastor, wrote.

It's unclear when the letter was published.

Court later, while appearing on a Christian radio station on Wednesday, compared transgender children to Hitler's Nazi regime and claimed tennis was 'full of lesbians' leading young players astray.

Court, who is now a pastor, told radio show Vision Christian Radio: 'Tennis is full of lesbians, because even when I was playing there was only a couple there, but those couple that led, that took young ones into parties and things.'

'And you know, what you get at the top is often what you'll get right through that sport,' she said.

'We're there to help them overcome. We're not against the people.'

She hit out at transgender children and said it was the 'all the devil', suggesting it was similar to Hitler's brainwashing in World War II.

'That's all the devil ... that's what Hitler did and that is what communism did... it got the mind of the children,' Court said.

Court made the bizarre link between Nazis and transgender children after she was asked about the prevalence of transgender athletes in Australian sport.

The former tennis star also said transgender children are a product of parents who 'don't care'.

'If you haven't got parents who bring you up that way and you have parents that don't care, and you're hurt and offended if somebody's saying something to you,' Court said.

Your child can just start to think 'Well maybe I am a girl', when they're a boy, or 'Maybe I'm a boy and I'm a girl'.'

Court also pointed out that her beloved sport tennis is now 'full of lesbians'.

'Even when I was playing there was only a couple there, but those couple that led, that took young ones into parties and things... because they like to be around heroes,' she said.

Following her controversial statements, tennis legend Martina Navratilova lashed out at the 74-year-old church pastor's 'sick and dangerous' comments on gays in tennis and transgender children.

Navratilova, who won 18 grand slam singles titles in 1978-90, said Court's views were so extreme Melbourne's Margaret Court Arena should be renamed.

'It is now clear exactly who Court is: An amazing tennis player, and a racist and a homophobe,' she wrote in a scathing letter in the Sydney Morning Herald.

The Czech-American star said she forgave Court for saying in 1990 that she was a bad role model because she was a lesbian, but her recent comments were 'sick and dangerous'.

She suggested Court's comments perpetuated a world where LGBT children were bashed, bullied and committed suicide because of intolerance.

'How much blood will be on Margaret's hands because kids will continue to get beaten for being different?' she wrote.

Navratilova said while Court was entitled to her opinion, free speech did not mean freedom from consequences of what she said.

'We should not be celebrating this kind of behaviour, this kind of philosophy. The platform people like Margaret Court use needs to be made smaller, not bigger,' she said.

Navratilova suggested the stadium be renamed after Aboriginal Australian 11-time tennis champion and former world number one Evonne Goolagong.

But Court remained defiant on Friday, saying renaming the stadium would be unfair and that she was being targeted by an American gay 'lobby'.

'I think I've won more Grand Slams than any man or woman and if it is (renamed), I don't believe I deserve it,' the 24-time Grand Slam singles champion told Melbourne's 3AW radio.

'They could probably get 100,000 petitions in 24 hours because that's how they work. There's a lot of money behind it, and it's coming from America.'

Asked if she thought a conspiracy was at work, Court replied: 'Yes, I believe there is... I think the (gay) lobby, yeah. They are a minority in number but they do have a lot of money behind them.'

She said there was 'a lot of bullying from the other way' and that she should have the right to express her views.

'My nephew, with the Margaret Court tennis academy in Albury, he's had his computers just trashed,' added Court.

'I don't want any more of it. Enough's enough but they will keep doing it and it's very militant and it's sad to think that. But really, I have nothing against them.'

Court said Navratilova, who is gay, 'needs to sort out her own nation, not our nation'.

'A lot of nations have gone to gay marriage, and I think this nation I don't believe needs to go that way. I think we need to stand our ground,' she said.

In defense of her same-sex marriage stance Court said: 'I think marriage is so important and children are so important. My thing is just about the definition of marriage.

'They (the LGBT community) can do what they want to do. I've got nothing against them. Just don't touch the definition in a Bible marriage.'

She said she doesn't dislike Martina personally, or any other female players and ensured listeners she doesn't take issue with gay people.

'I've got them in the church. I've also got over a hundred Africans in my church and they know I love them,' Court said.

Court later told Melbourne radio she accepts transgender people.

'That's their choice what they do with their life and I think it's very sad people in that area feel that that is right,' she told 3AW on Friday.

Tennis Australia and the operator of the Margaret Court Arena, Melbourne and Olympic Parks, have distanced themselves from Court's views on gay marriage.

Goolagong Cawley, a seven-time Grand Slam champion, was the first Aborigine to represent her country in world tennis and was only the second mother to win Wimbledon, in 1980.

World number one Andy Murray, 18-times grand slam champion Navratilova and several Australian players including Samantha Stosur, Nick Kyrgios and Jamiee Fourlis expressed disapproval of Court's comments.
